Text.Value: You! There are spawn flooding out of that dungeon - what possessed you to release them?
Thank you, I only want to live in peace.
Killing his spawn means killing your children.
They're in the Underdark, they won't bother you.
I would not be so hasty. You have trials still to face - you may want allies.
I cannot say if I'm more impressed by your bravery or your terrible luck to face such a foe.
I pray they will stay there. Although who knows what events this has set in motion.
None of us need resort to harsh words. We are still friends here.
You gave them peace. For that, for all you have done, you have our thanks.
Do not use our tragedy to justify your sins!
I'm sorry, but I couldn't save your children.
Until then, go in peace. And thank you.
Our children have been twice taken from us: first by the vampire spawn and now by you. But they will be avenged.
The beast is dead and that is what matters. Our children are avenged, if nothing else.
I took care of the vampire. I'm sure you can handle his spawn without me.
You! We ask you to free our children and you unleash thousands of vampire spawn on the Sword Coast?

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Released Spawns, got quest to kill Cazador

Text.Value: Peace was the best I could give them. I'm sorry I couldn't do more.
They were innocent - it would've been wrong to kill them.
You are as monstrous as him. Perhaps more so, because you choose this path.
Cazador's dead, your kids are free - that's what you asked for.
We will find your vampire and end his blight on this land. But first, we deal with you.
As for our children... we shall see what can be done.
A stranger who faced down the Vampire Ascendant and lived.
Hold there! Didn't expect to see anyone with a pulse coming out of that dungeon.
Yes, you can tell your pale companion he has nothing to fear.
You deal with it. Surely you can manage that.
As are we all but this is the hand fate has dealt. We will carry them in our hearts.
Let's go with the first one.
It was nothing, I'm surprised he beat you so badly.
You'd prefer I killed your children?
We meet again. A pity we had to meet like this.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Astarion Ascended and we met Gur, but we didn't receive the quest.

Text.Value: I fear none of us will see peace yet. There are still trials ahead.
You could have stopped Astarion. You could have saved our children. Instead?

EditorData.NodeContext: Next line: "one blood-sucking beast replaced with another."

Text.Value: You have my people's thanks. There will be dark times ahead for us all, but we will stand with you as best we can.
Perhaps you were right to leave things as you did. We should finish this ourselves.
You leave with your work half done? Cazador may be dead, but you would leave thousands of spawn trapped in those cages?
At last, we see you as the monster you are.
With his old master dead and our children at rest, we will pursue him no more.
That was not your choice to make! If nothing else we could have said goodbye.
You, who destroyed the vampire lord, but released thousands of his spawn?
I pray they can resist the urges of their new nature. But we shall see.
And I hope I never see any of you again.
However reluctantly, I cannot fault your logic. You did everything that was asked of you.
You did the best you could in an impossible situation. No one could ask for more.
Unless he gives us reason to.
We sent you here on a mission of mercy, and what do we find?

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Astarion Ascended, we got the quest to kill Cazador

Text.Value: I understand. Although I wonder how many other innocents will die for your mercy.
Until then, go in peace.
Your children were vampire spawn - they were dead long before I got there.
He attacked us, stole our children, and left our tribe shattered.
Of course not! I just wish - ... I do not know. I wish this had all passed us by.
For what it's worth, I'm sorry. I wish I could bring your children back.
But you have my people's thanks - when it is time for you to face those trials, we will stand with you.
And be clear that he owes it all to you.
I understand perfectly. I have never seen anything so clearly.
I killed seven thousand monsters today, I can kill a few ungrateful hunters too.
If such a time comes, if you need help, we will stand with you.
Tell Astarion he is free. Never again will he be hunted by my people.
We fight against evil wherever we find it. And I find it standing before me now.
That leaves only the matter of your pale companion.
We offer no gold, but we do give you a promise.
Why? What madness possessed you?
So, is it true? You killed Cazador and all of his prisoners? Including the children he took from us?

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Spawns Dead, don't know about Children, met Ulma

Text.Value: His sins against us are great. But so too are the deeds you have done today.
The few of us that survived came here looking for revenge. But what do we find instead?

EditorData.NodeContext: This line could be followed by an aggressive line ("one blood-sucking beast replaced with another") or an impressed line ("A stranger who faced down the Vampire Ascendant and lived.") so it needs to be tonally neutral

Text.Value: There is no walking away from this. There is no hiding from the evil you have unleashed.
I'm sorry, I didn't know your children were in those cells.
I admit, I was not sure I would ever see you again. But you faced down the Vampire Ascendant and lived.
...That's it? No reward?
Very well, we will do what needs to be done.
Alas, you may be right. You had few choices, all bad.
As for your pale companion, we will hunt him no longer. Unless he gives us cause to.
We will make it our duty to find the spawn that escaped into the Underdark. Especially our children.
I took care of Cazador, so I assume you'll leave Astarion alone now?
Cazador and his spawn dead. And our children with them.

EditorData.NodeContext: Bitter about the death of their children

Text.Value: So, is it true? Cazador is dead by your hand, and so are our children?
Your children were vampire spawn - they were already dead.
As for you, you have my people's thanks. I know you face trials ahead - we will stand with you as best we can.
Thank you for giving us this choice. For giving us a chance to see them one last time.
I notice your pale companion's absence, but tell him he need not fear us.
A pity such an impressive feat came on the heels of our children's tragedy, but you were not responsible for their deaths.
They were our little ones! If nothing else, we could have said goodbye.
You don't understand, Astarion needed to do this.
I know you face trials ahead. But when it is time, you will not face them alone. We will stand with you as best we can.
That is... difficult to hear.
But you were given an impossible choice. Who's to say what path was right.
One blood-sucking beast replaced with another. Our children sacrificed to birth a monster.
Until then, go in peace. And thank you.
Don't worry, you'll join your children soon.
If your children were vampire spawn, they were dead long before I got there.
My name's Ulma, my people are monster hunters. But the vampire Cazador made us his prey.
You won't win this fight, but you can still walk away with your lives.

Synopsis: Dialog with the Gur Leader after you defeated Cazador
